    "models": {
        "NOxPhotochemistry": {
            "reference": {
                "notes": "source_ref: GasChem.jl@8c12c048482b515fb8eb2110bf8ab4b4f4e71309:src/nox_photochemistry.jl:88\n\nUpstream `NOxPhotochemistry` is an MTK `@component` with 9 `@variables` (5 inputs NO/NO2/O3/O2/M + 4 outputs O/O3_pss/О¦/P_O3), 3 `@parameters` (j_NO2, k_O_O2_M, k_NO_O3), 0 `@constants`, and 4 algebraic equations from S&P В§6.2 (Eqs. 6.5-6.8). It returns `System(eqs, t; name)` вЂ” a system carrying the time independent variable `t` but with no `D(В·)` time-derivative operator in any equation; the upstream tests and doc page compile it with `mtkcompile(sys; inputs=[NO, NO2, O3, O2, M])` and solve it as a `NonlinearProblem` with the five inputs pinned to user-supplied concentrations.\n\nVariable-classification convention: the five input @variables (NO, NO2, O3, O2, M) are encoded here as `type: parameter` because they have no defining equation within the NOxPhotochemistry component itself вЂ” they are externally-supplied inputs that the upstream compile treats via `inputs=[...]` to NonlinearProblem. This mirrors the rig-wide convention applied by sibling oh_production.esm (the upstream input @variables Oв‚ѓ/Hв‚‚O/M are encoded as parameters) and typical.esm/urban.esm/remote.esm (upstream air-composition species encoded as parameters). The four output @variables (O, O3_pss, О¦, P_O3) are encoded as `type: state` because each has exactly one defining algebraic equation that the inline-test runner solves as part of the post-mtkcompile observed-binding layer. The upstream structural test `NOxPhotochemistry: Structural Verification` (test/test_nox_photochemistry.jl:4-31) asserts `length(unknowns(sys)) == 9`, `length(equations(sys)) == 4`, and `length(parameters(sys)) == 3` вЂ” the .esm preserves this with the 9 declared variables (5 parameter + 4 state), 4 entries in the `equations` array, and 3 rate-constant parameters.\n\nObservability classification: this component is purely algebraic вЂ” every output variable is the LHS of one algebraic equation in the inputs and rate-constant parameters (no derivative; the `(t)` time index has no role since there is no `D(В·)` operator in any equation). Test scenarios use `time_span: [0.0, 1.0]` and sample at t=0 to mirror the convention used by sibling observed-only ESM files (oh_production.esm, gwp.esm, photon_energy.esm, stefan_boltzmann.esm, wien.esm). For an algebraic-only system the trajectory is constant in time and converges to the same fixed point in one nonlinear-solver step regardless of the sampling time.\n\nRate-constant CGSв†’SI translation: the upstream Julia declares the rate constants as SI-converted CGS values via explicit multiplication:\n  j_NO2     = 8.0e-3 sвЃ»В№                  (typical midday NOв‚‚ photolysis rate, S&P В§6.2; first-order, no conversion)\n  k_O_O2_M  = 6.0e-34 В· 1.0e-12 mвЃ¶/s      (O + Oв‚‚ + M в†’ Oв‚ѓ termolecular; CGS 6.0e-34 cmвЃ¶/molecВІ/s Г— 1e-12 cmвЃ¶в†’mвЃ¶ factor)\n  k_NO_O3   = 1.9e-14 В· 1.0e-6  mВі/s      (NO + Oв‚ѓ в†’ NOв‚‚ + Oв‚‚ bimolecular; CGS 1.9e-14 cmВі/molec/s Г— 1e-6 cmВів†’mВі factor, S&P p. 211)\nThe products evaluate in IEEE-754 Float64 to exactly the clean literals: `6.0e-34 * 1.0e-12 == 6.0e-46` and `1.9e-14 * 1.0e-6 == 1.9e-20` (both bit-identical вЂ” verified), so the .esm encodes the SI defaults directly as 6.0e-46 and 1.9e-20.\n\nInput-variable defaults: the five input @variables carry no upstream default (MTK @variables, unlike @parameters, have no `= value`). The .esm assigns each input a `default` taken from the upstream test's typical-midday scenario (test/test_nox_photochemistry.jl `NOxPhotochemistry: Eq 6.5/6.6` testitems, lines 54-111): NO = 2.5e16 mвЃ»Ві (~1 ppb at STP), NO2 = 5.0e16 mвЃ»Ві (~2 ppb), O3 = 1.0e18 mвЃ»Ві (~40 ppb tropospheric background), O2 = 5.25e24 mвЃ»Ві (21% of STP air number density), M = 2.5e25 mвЃ»Ві (STP total air number density). This matches the rig convention used by sibling oh_production.esm (input defaults from the upstream test typical scenario).\n\nEquation structure: the four outputs are mutually independent вЂ” each depends only on inputs and rate-constant parameters, with no inter-output references (unlike the oh_production.esm cascade where P_OH references Оµ_OH). All four share the numerator j_NO2В·NO2. Eq. 6.5 (O) and Eqs. 6.6/6.7/6.8 use distinct denominators. O3_pss (Eq. 6.6) is independent of the O3 input; О¦ (Eq. 6.7) and P_O3 (Eq. 6.8) depend on O3. At the typical-midday defaults O3_pss = 8.42e17 mвЃ»Ві, which is below the default O3 input of 1.0e18 mвЃ»Ві, so the default О¦ = 0.842 < 1 and P_O3 = -7.5e13 mвЃ»Ві/s < 0 (net ozone loss вЂ” the default O3 sits above its photostationary value).\n\nNumerical defaults (S&P typical-midday surface conditions, SI):\n  At NO=2.5e16, NO2=5.0e16, O3=1.0e18, O2=5.25e24, M=2.5e25:\n  O      = 8.0e-3В·5.0e16 / (6.0e-46В·5.25e24В·2.5e25) = 5.079365e9 mвЃ»Ві  (short-lived ground-state O atom)\n  O3_pss = 8.0e-3В·5.0e16 / (1.9e-20В·2.5e16)        = 8.421053e17 mвЃ»Ві (~34 ppb вЂ” the Leighton value; S&P hand-calc в‰€ 8.42e17)\n  О¦      = 8.0e-3В·5.0e16 / (1.9e-20В·2.5e16В·1.0e18)  = 0.8421053       (< 1: default O3 exceeds its PSS value)\n  P_O3   = 8.0e-3В·5.0e16 в€’ 1.9e-20В·2.5e16В·1.0e18    = -7.5e13 mвЃ»Ві/s   (< 0: net ozone loss at the default state)\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1.0e-10 / abs=1.0e-12): the four algebraic equations are small expression trees (2-4 IEEE-754 ops each вЂ” Eq. 6.5 is two multiplications + one division for the numerator/denominator plus the joining division; Eq. 6.8 is two multiplications + one subtraction). Each output is correctly-rounded to within ~1 ULP в‰€ 1e-16 relative; rel=1.0e-10 leaves 6 orders of magnitude of headroom over the IEEE-754 floor and is comfortably tighter than the upstream rtol bounds (rtol=0.05 for the Eq. 6.6 hand-calc cross-check, rtol=1.0e-6 for the О¦-at-PSS and O3_pss-linearity identities). The abs=1.0e-12 floor handles the P_O3-at-photostationary-state boundary case where the j_NO2В·NO2 в€’ k_NO_O3В·NOВ·O3 near-cancellation collapses to IEEE-754 exact zero. Matches the convention used by sibling observed-only ESM files: oh_production.esm at rel=1e-10/abs=1e-12, stefan_boltzmann.esm at rel=1e-10/abs=1e-12, wien.esm at rel=1e-10, gwp.esm at rel=1e-10.\n\nUnit balance (verified): all four equations balance dimensionally.\n  Eq. 6.5 `O ~ j_NO2В·NO2 / (k_O_O2_MВ·O2В·M)`: (sвЃ»В№В·mвЃ»Ві) / ((mвЃ¶/s)В·mвЃ»ВіВ·mвЃ»Ві) = (mвЃ»Ві/s) / (sвЃ»В№) = mвЃ»Ві вњ“\n  Eq. 6.6 `O3_pss ~ j_NO2В·NO2 / (k_NO_O3В·NO)`: (sвЃ»В№В·mвЃ»Ві) / ((mВі/s)В·mвЃ»Ві) = (mвЃ»Ві/s) / (sвЃ»В№) = mвЃ»Ві вњ“\n  Eq. 6.7 `О¦ ~ j_NO2В·NO2 / (k_NO_O3В·NOВ·O3)`: (sвЃ»В№В·mвЃ»Ві) / ((mВі/s)В·mвЃ»ВіВ·mвЃ»Ві) = (mвЃ»Ві/s) / (mвЃ»Ві/s) = dimensionless вњ“\n  Eq. 6.8 `P_O3 ~ j_NO2В·NO2 в€’ k_NO_O3В·NOВ·O3`: (sвЃ»В№В·mвЃ»Ві) в€’ ((mВі/s)В·mвЃ»ВіВ·mвЃ»Ві) = mвЃ»ВіВ·sвЃ»В№ в€’ mвЃ»ВіВ·sвЃ»В№ = mвЃ»ВіВ·sвЃ»В№ вњ“\nThe migrated .esm preserves the upstream units verbatim вЂ” all concentrations in SI mвЃ»Ві, j_NO2 in sвЃ»В№, k_NO_O3 in mВі/s (bimolecular), k_O_O2_M in mвЃ¶/s (termolecular), О¦ dimensionless, P_O3 in mвЃ»ВіВ·sвЃ»В№. SI throughout; no unit conversion at parse or runtime.\n\nUpstream test reproduction (test/test_nox_photochemistry.jl):\n- `NOxPhotochemistry: Structural Verification` (lines 4-31): 9 unknowns / 4 equations / 3 parameters and required output names O3_pss, P_O3 вЂ” reproduced by the .esm structural shape (5 parameter + 4 state variables under `variables`, 4 entries in `equations`).\n- `NOxPhotochemistry: Eq 6.5 O Atom Steady-State` (lines 54-79): asserts 0 < O < 1.0e12 at the typical scenario вЂ” reproduced and tightened by `typical_midday_all_outputs` pinning the exact O = 5079365079.365079 mвЃ»Ві (well inside the 0..1e12 band), and by `o_atom_linear_in_j_no2` / `o_atom_inverse_in_air_density` exercising Eq. 6.5's structural linearity in j_NO2 and inverse dependence on M.\n- `NOxPhotochemistry: Eq 6.6 Leighton Relationship` (lines 81-111): asserts 1.0e17 < O3_pss < 1.0e19 and O3_pss в‰€ 8.42e17 at rtol=0.05 вЂ” reproduced and tightened by `typical_midday_all_outputs` pinning the exact O3_pss = 8.421052631578948e17 mвЃ»Ві at rel=1e-10.\n- `NOxPhotochemistry: Eq 6.7 Photostationary State Parameter` (lines 113-148): asserts О¦ в‰€ 1.0 at O3 = O3_pss (rtol=1e-6), О¦ > 1 below PSS, О¦ < 1 above PSS вЂ” reproduced by `phi_unity_at_photostationary_state` (О¦ = 1.0 at O3 = O3_pss), `phi_above_unity_below_pss` (О¦ = 2.0 at O3 = 0.5В·O3_pss), `phi_below_unity_above_pss` (О¦ = 0.5 at O3 = 2В·O3_pss).\n- `NOxPhotochemistry: Eq 6.8 Net O3 Production` (lines 150-184): asserts |P_O3|/(j_NO2В·NO2) < 1e-6 at PSS, P_O3 > 0 below PSS, P_O3 < 0 above PSS вЂ” reproduced by `phi_unity_at_photostationary_state` (P_O3 = 0 at O3 = O3_pss), `phi_above_unity_below_pss` (P_O3 = +2.0e14 below PSS), `phi_below_unity_above_pss` (P_O3 = -4.0e14 above PSS).\n- `NOxPhotochemistry: Rate Constants at 298 K` (lines 189-200): asserts the default values of j_NO2, k_O_O2_M, k_NO_O3 вЂ” implicitly covered by the `default` fields declared on each parameter; the structural-test gate verifies they are bit-identical to the upstream Julia values.\n- `NOxPhotochemistry: O3_pss Scales with NO2/NO Ratio` (lines 205-228): asserts O3_pss(NO2=2e16)/O3_pss(NO2=1e16) в‰€ 2.0 at rtol=1e-6 вЂ” reproduced by `o3_pss_linear_in_no2_baseline` and `o3_pss_linear_in_no2_doubled` pinning both endpoints (4.210526315789474e17 and 8.421052631578948e17) at rel=1e-10 so the ratio is exact by IEEE-754 multiplication-by-2 reproducibility; `o3_pss_inverse_in_no` additionally pins the 1/[NO] dependence and `o3_pss_independent_of_o3_input` confirms Eq. 6.6's independence of the O3 input.\nThe upstream tests pin only qualitative bounds and one rtol=0.05 hand-calc; the migrated .esm tests upgrade these to quantitative value pins at rel=1e-10, a strict tightening вЂ” every upstream qualitative assertion is implied by the more-specific pinned value. Additional regime tests (`polluted_urban_high_nox`, `clean_remote_low_nox`) exercise all four outputs across the urban-to-remote NOx range for full regression coverage."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1.0e-10,
                "abs": 1.0e-12
            },
            "variables": {
                "j_NO2": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "s^-1",
                    "default": 8.0e-3,
                    "description": "NOв‚‚ photolysis rate j_{NOв‚‚} [sвЃ»В№] for NOв‚‚ + hОЅ в†’ NO + O (О» < 424 nm). The upstream default 8.0e-3 sвЃ»В№ is the canonical typical-midday surface value (S&P В§6.2) вЂ” clear-sky, solar zenith angle near noon. j_NO2 is the engine of the whole NOx cycle: it sets the rate of O-atom production (Eq. 6.5) and, together with k_NO_O3, fixes the photostationary-state ozone level (Eq. 6.6). Highly variable in practice вЂ” it drops to zero at night, scales with sec(SZA) through the day, and increases with altitude as the overhead Oв‚ѓ column thins. Overridable for diurnal, seasonal, or altitude scenarios; in the full TroposphericChemistrySystem it is supplied by the upstream FastJX photolysis subsystem via param_to_var coupling."
                },
                "k_O_O2_M": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^6/s",
                    "default": 6.0e-46,
                    "description": "Termolecular rate constant for O + Oв‚‚ + M в†’ Oв‚ѓ + M [mвЃ¶ sвЃ»В№]. The upstream default is the SI-converted CGS value 6.0e-34 cmвЃ¶ molecвЃ»ВІ sвЃ»В№ Г— 1e-12 (cmвЃ¶в†’mвЃ¶) = 6.0e-46 mвЃ¶/s (the upstream Julia writes the literal product `6.0e-34 * 1.0e-12`, which evaluates to exactly 6.0e-46 in IEEE-754 Float64). This is the recombination step that converts the O atom from NOв‚‚ photolysis into ozone; it appears only in Eq. 6.5 as part of the O-atom loss denominator k_O_O2_MВ·[Oв‚‚]В·[M]. The very large quenching rate k_O_O2_MВ·[Oв‚‚]В·[M] в‰€ 7.9e4 sвЃ»В№ at STP makes the ground-state O atom extremely short-lived (~13 Вµs), which is why Eq. 6.5 is a valid steady-state relation."
                },
                "k_NO_O3": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/s",
                    "default": 1.9e-20,
                    "description": "Bimolecular rate constant for NO + Oв‚ѓ в†’ NOв‚‚ + Oв‚‚ [mВі sвЃ»В№]. The upstream default is the SI-converted CGS value 1.9e-14 cmВі molecвЃ»В№ sвЃ»В№ Г— 1e-6 (cmВів†’mВі) = 1.9e-20 mВі/s (S&P p. 211; the upstream Julia writes the literal product `1.9e-14 * 1.0e-6`, exactly 1.9e-20 in Float64). This is the ozone-titration step that closes the NOx cycle by reconverting NO to NOв‚‚. It sets the photostationary-state ozone level (Eq. 6.6: O3_pss в€ќ j_NO2/k_NO_O3) and the ozone-loss term of the net production rate (Eq. 6.8). Weakly temperature-dependent in reality (Arrhenius); the upstream uses the temperature-independent ~298 K value for the algebraic system."
                },
                "NO": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 2.5e16,
                    "description": "Nitric oxide number density [mвЃ»Ві] (externally-supplied input). The default 2.5e16 mвЃ»Ві в‰€ 1 ppb at STP is the upstream test's typical-midday value (test/test_nox_photochemistry.jl:59). NO appears in the denominators of Eqs. 6.6/6.7 and the loss term of Eq. 6.8 вЂ” higher NO lowers the photostationary-state ozone (O3_pss в€ќ 1/[NO]) and raises the Oв‚ѓ-titration loss. Encoded as `type: parameter` (not `type: state`) because NOxPhotochemistry has no governing equation for NO вЂ” it is purely an input. In the full TroposphericChemistrySystem NO is provided by the upstream NOx-emission and chemistry subsystems; in standalone tests it is overridden via `parameter_overrides`. Tropospheric range ~2.5e14 (remote, 0.01 ppb) to ~2.5e18 (polluted urban, 100 ppb)."
                },
                "NO2": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 5.0e16,
                    "description": "Nitrogen dioxide number density [mвЃ»Ві] (externally-supplied input). The default 5.0e16 mвЃ»Ві в‰€ 2 ppb at STP is the upstream test's typical-midday value (test/test_nox_photochemistry.jl:60). NOв‚‚ is the photolytic source of the cycle: it appears in the numerator j_NO2В·[NOв‚‚] of all four equations, so every output scales linearly with NOв‚‚. The photostationary-state ozone is proportional to the [NOв‚‚]/[NO] ratio (Eq. 6.6, the Leighton relationship). Encoded as `type: parameter` for the same reason as NO вЂ” it is an external input with no defining equation in this component."
                },
                "O3": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 1.0e18,
                    "description": "Ozone number density [mвЃ»Ві] (externally-supplied input вЂ” the measured/ambient Oв‚ѓ, distinct from the diagnostic O3_pss output). The default 1.0e18 mвЃ»Ві в‰€ 40 ppb at STP is the upstream test's typical tropospheric background (test/test_nox_photochemistry.jl:61). O3 enters Eq. 6.7 (О¦) and Eq. 6.8 (P_O3) вЂ” comparing the ambient O3 against the photostationary value O3_pss is exactly what О¦ measures: О¦ = O3_pss/O3, so О¦ > 1 when ambient O3 is below its PSS value (net production) and О¦ < 1 when above (net loss). O3 does NOT enter Eq. 6.6 вЂ” O3_pss is independent of the ambient O3 input. Encoded as `type: parameter`: an external input with no governing equation here."
                },
                "O2": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 5.25e24,
                    "description": "Molecular oxygen number density [mвЃ»Ві] (externally-supplied input). The default 5.25e24 mвЃ»Ві is 21% of the STP total air number density (2.5e25), i.e. the well-mixed atmospheric Oв‚‚ fraction. Oв‚‚ appears only in Eq. 6.5 as part of the O-atom quenching denominator k_O_O2_MВ·[Oв‚‚]В·[M] (the Oв‚‚ is the reactant that recombines with the O atom to form Oв‚ѓ). Encoded as `type: parameter`: an external input. Like M it decreases with altitude in lockstep with total air density (the mixing ratio stays ~constant below the homopause)."
                },
                "M": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 2.5e25,
                    "description": "Total air number density [mвЃ»Ві] (externally-supplied input). The default 2.5e25 mвЃ»Ві is the STP value used by the upstream test (test/test_nox_photochemistry.jl:63) and by sibling typical.esm. M is the third body in the O + Oв‚‚ + M в†’ Oв‚ѓ recombination and appears only in Eq. 6.5's O-atom quenching denominator. M decreases roughly exponentially with altitude (scale height ~8 km in the troposphere): ~1e25 at 12 km, ~1e24 at 30 km. Encoded as `type: parameter`: an external input supplied by the upstream transport/thermodynamics module."
                },
                "O": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "description": "Ground-state atomic oxygen O(ВіP) steady-state number density [mвЃ»Ві] (Eq. 6.5). Algebraic balance between production from NOв‚‚ photolysis (j_NO2В·[NOв‚‚]) and loss by recombination with Oв‚‚ (k_O_O2_MВ·[Oв‚‚]В·[M]): O = j_NO2В·[NOв‚‚] / (k_O_O2_MВ·[Oв‚‚]В·[M]). At the typical-midday default conditions O в‰€ 5.08e9 mвЃ»Ві вЂ” extremely low, because the O atom is consumed within ~13 Вµs by the fast three-body recombination. The 'steady-state' label reflects the quasi-equilibrium assumption: the O-atom lifetime is far shorter than any other timescale in the cycle, so its concentration tracks the instantaneous NOв‚‚ photolysis rate. Linear in j_NO2 and in [NOв‚‚]; inversely proportional to [Oв‚‚] and [M]."
                },
                "O3_pss": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "description": "Photostationary-state ozone number density [mвЃ»Ві] (Eq. 6.6 вЂ” the Leighton relationship). The ozone concentration the NO-NOв‚‚-Oв‚ѓ cycle would reach in pure photochemical equilibrium: O3_pss = j_NO2В·[NOв‚‚] / (k_NO_O3В·[NO]). Proportional to the [NOв‚‚]/[NO] ratio and to j_NO2/k_NO_O3. At the typical-midday defaults O3_pss в‰€ 8.42e17 mвЃ»Ві (~34 ppb). Independent of the ambient O3 input вЂ” O3_pss is what the cycle predicts, not what is measured. In real urban air the measured O3 deviates from O3_pss because peroxy radicals (HOв‚‚, ROв‚‚) provide an extra NOв†’NOв‚‚ pathway beyond NO + Oв‚ѓ; that deviation is quantified by О¦."
                },
                "О¦": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Photostationary-state parameter О¦, dimensionless (Eq. 6.7). The ratio of the NOв‚‚-photolysis ozone source to the NO+Oв‚ѓ ozone sink: О¦ = j_NO2В·[NOв‚‚] / (k_NO_O3В·[NO]В·[Oв‚ѓ]) = O3_pss/O3. О¦ = 1 marks exact photostationary state (pure NO-NOв‚‚-Oв‚ѓ cycling, no net ozone change). О¦ > 1 means the ambient Oв‚ѓ is below its photostationary value вЂ” additional oxidants (HOв‚‚, ROв‚‚ peroxy radicals) are converting NO to NOв‚‚ without consuming Oв‚ѓ, driving net ozone production; typical urban daytime measurements show О¦ в‰€ 1.5-3. О¦ < 1 means ambient Oв‚ѓ exceeds its PSS value вЂ” net ozone loss. At the typical-midday defaults О¦ в‰€ 0.842 (the default O3 input of 40 ppb sits above the 34 ppb photostationary value)."
                },
                "P_O3": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "Net ozone production rate [mвЃ»Ві sвЃ»В№] (Eq. 6.8). The difference between the NOв‚‚-photolysis ozone source and the NO+Oв‚ѓ ozone sink: P_O3 = j_NO2В·[NOв‚‚] в€’ k_NO_O3В·[NO]В·[Oв‚ѓ]. Positive when the system is below photostationary state (ambient Oв‚ѓ < O3_pss в†’ net production), negative when above (net loss), and zero at exact PSS вЂ” P_O3 and О¦ are two views of the same departure from equilibrium (P_O3 = j_NO2В·[NOв‚‚]В·(1 в€’ 1/О¦)). At the typical-midday defaults P_O3 в‰€ -7.5e13 mвЃ»Ві/s (net loss, since the default O3 exceeds O3_pss). This is the chemical tendency the NO-NOв‚‚-Oв‚ѓ cycle alone would impose on ozone; the full tropospheric tendency adds the peroxy-radical channels that NOxPhotochemistry deliberately omits."
                }
            },
            "equations": [
                {
                    "lhs": "O",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "/",
                        "args": [
                            {"op": "*", "args": ["j_NO2", "NO2"]},
                            {"op": "*", "args": ["k_O_O2_M", "O2", "M"]}
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "lhs": "O3_pss",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "/",
                        "args": [
                            {"op": "*", "args": ["j_NO2", "NO2"]},
                            {"op": "*", "args": ["k_NO_O3", "NO"]}
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "lhs": "О¦",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "/",
                        "args": [
                            {"op": "*", "args": ["j_NO2", "NO2"]},
                            {"op": "*", "args": ["k_NO_O3", "NO", "O3"]}
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "lhs": "P_O3",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "-",
                        "args": [
                            {"op": "*", "args": ["j_NO2", "NO2"]},
                            {"op": "*", "args": ["k_NO_O3", "NO", "O3"]}
                        ]
                    }
                }
            ],
            "tests": [
                {
                    "id": "typical_midday_all_outputs",
                    "description": "Anchor test at the upstream typical-midday scenario (NO=2.5e16 ~1 ppb, NO2=5.0e16 ~2 ppb, O3=1.0e18 ~40 ppb, O2=5.25e24, M=2.5e25 вЂ” test/test_nox_photochemistry.jl:59-63). Reproduces and tightens two upstream testitems at once: `Eq 6.5 O Atom Steady-State` (asserts 0 < O < 1.0e12 вЂ” here O = 5.08e9, well inside the band) and `Eq 6.6 Leighton Relationship` (asserts 1e17 < O3_pss < 1e19 and O3_pss в‰€ 8.42e17 at rtol=0.05 вЂ” here O3_pss pinned exactly at 8.421052631578948e17). All four outputs are pinned at rel=1e-10. Note O3_pss = 8.42e17 < O3 = 1.0e18, so О¦ = 0.842 < 1 and P_O3 < 0 вЂ” the default ambient ozone sits above its photostationary value.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {},
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "O", "time": 0.0, "expected": 5079365079.365079},
                        {"variable": "O3_pss", "time": 0.0, "expected": 8.421052631578948e+17},
                        {"variable": "О¦", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.8421052631578947},
                        {"variable": "P_O3", "time": 0.0, "expected": -75000000000000.0}
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "phi_unity_at_photostationary_state",
                    "description": "Reproduces the upstream `Eq 6.7 Photostationary State Parameter` and `Eq 6.8 Net O3 Production` at-PSS cases (test/test_nox_photochemistry.jl:127-137, 164-173). The ambient O3 is overridden to the photostationary value O3_pss = j_NO2В·NO2/(k_NO_O3В·NO) = 8.421052631578948e17 mвЃ»Ві computed at the default NO/NO2. At exact photostationary state О¦ = O3_pss/O3 = 1.0 and the net ozone production P_O3 = j_NO2В·NO2 в€’ k_NO_O3В·NOВ·O3 = 0.0 (the source exactly balances the sink). The upstream asserts О¦ в‰€ 1.0 at rtol=1e-6 and |P_O3|/(j_NO2В·NO2) < 1e-6; this test pins О¦ = 1.0 exactly and P_O3 = 0.0 with an abs tolerance of 1.0 (the IEEE-754 near-cancellation residual is sub-ULP вЂ” far below the upstream's 4e8 'effectively zero' threshold).",
                    "parameter_overrides": {"O3": 8.421052631578948e+17},
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "О¦", "time": 0.0, "expected": 1.0},
                        {"variable": "P_O3", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.0, "tolerance": {"abs": 1.0}}
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "phi_above_unity_below_pss",
                    "description": "Reproduces the upstream `Eq 6.7`/`Eq 6.8` below-PSS cases (test/test_nox_photochemistry.jl:140-142, 176-178). The ambient O3 is overridden to half the photostationary value (0.5В·O3_pss = 4.210526315789474e17 mвЃ»Ві). Below photostationary state the NOв‚‚-photolysis source outruns the NO+Oв‚ѓ sink: О¦ = O3_pss/O3 = 2.0 > 1 (the upstream asserts О¦ > 1) and the net ozone production P_O3 = +2.0e14 mвЃ»Ві/s > 0 (the upstream asserts P_O3 > 0). Physically this is the regime where peroxy-radical chemistry would be driving ozone formation. Both outputs pinned at rel=1e-10.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {"O3": 4.210526315789474e+17},
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "О¦", "time": 0.0, "expected": 2.0},
                        {"variable": "P_O3", "time": 0.0, "expected": 200000000000000.0}
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "phi_below_unity_above_pss",
                    "description": "Reproduces the upstream `Eq 6.7`/`Eq 6.8` above-PSS cases (test/test_nox_photochemistry.jl:145-147, 181-183). The ambient O3 is overridden to twice the photostationary value (2.0В·O3_pss = 1.6842105263157896e18 mвЃ»Ві). Above photostationary state the NO+Oв‚ѓ sink outruns the NOв‚‚-photolysis source: О¦ = O3_pss/O3 = 0.5 < 1 (the upstream asserts О¦ < 1) and the net ozone production P_O3 = -4.0e14 mвЃ»Ві/s < 0 (the upstream asserts P_O3 < 0) вЂ” net ozone loss. Both outputs pinned at rel=1e-10.",
